        {
          "h": "Design Process",
          "html": "01\n<h3>Concept and Architecture</h3>\n<p>\n The starting point was the notebook problem. Physical notebooks work because they're\n always present, always visible, and have no competing demands on your attention. But\n they lose to apps on organization, search, and persistence across days. The STIK-eNote\n was designed to keep everything that makes a notebook effective while fixing what paper\n is structurally bad at.\n </p>\n<p>\n The clamshell form factor followed directly from that: the ePaper display on the back\n shows the task list whether the device is on or off, and the TFT and keyboard inside\n only come on when you need to edit. The magnetic lid-detect mechanism ties the two\n states together without requiring the user to press anything. Early work focused on\n selecting the MCU (ESP32-S3 over PocketBeagle for its integrated PSRAM, dual-core\n architecture, and deep sleep support) and confirming the peripheral assignments — two\n independent SPI buses for the displays, I²C for the keyboard.\n </p>\n02\n<h3>Schematic Design and Hand-Wire Prototype</h3>\n<p>\n The schematic was designed from scratch in KiCad across five sheets, each covering one\n functional subsystem: top-level pin routing, power path (boost converter, LDO, charger),\n USB-C input, ESP32-S3 peripheral connections, and I²C level shifting. This separation\n made the schematic readable for review and set the layout up for clean PCB routing.\n </p>\n<p>\n In parallel, a hand-wired prototype using off-the-shelf modules validated the circuit\n topology and firmware against real hardware. This is the build the firmware currently\n runs on. The prototype confirmed that separate SPI buses were mandatory (shared bus\n caused consistent failures during early bring-up) and that the ePaper initialization\n sequence had to come before the TFT or both displays ended up in undefined states.\n </p>\n03\n<h3>Firmware and PlatformIO Build</h3>\n<p>\n The firmware was built with PlatformIO using the Arduino framework on FreeRTOS. The\n dual-core split — keyboard polling on Core 0, display rendering on Core 1 — was the\n key architectural decision. A FreeRTOS queue between them means neither core can\n stall the other, which is essential given how slow SPI display writes are.\n </p>\n<p>\n Building requires Python 3 and the PlatformIO CLI. Copy the custom board definition,\n then compile and upload:\n </p>\n<pre>python3 -m pip install -U platformio\nmkdir -p ~/.platformio/boards && cp esp32-s3-devkitc-1-n16r8v.json ~/.platformio/boards/\npython3 -m platformio run -e esp32-s3-devkitc-1-n16r8v\npython3 -m platformio run -t upload -e esp32-s3-devkitc-1-n16r8v</pre>\n<p>\n On first boot, the device initializes both buses in sequence (ePaper first, then TFT),\n loads any saved tasks and events from NVS, and drops into the task list view.\n Navigation is arrow keys, Enter to select, <code>a</code> to add a task,\n <code>c</code> for calendar, <code>p</code> for pomodoro. The device auto-sleeps\n after inactivity and wakes on any keypress or when the lid opens.\n </p>\n<p>\n The current prototype is hand-assembled from off-the-shelf modules. PCB files are in\n the repository for anyone who wants to take it further; gerbers, schematics, BOM,\n and KiCad project files all live in <code>project_02/hardware</code>.\n </p>\n04\n<h3>PCB Layout in KiCad</h3>\n<p>\n With the schematic finalized and the hand-wire prototype proving out the design, the\n PCB layout consolidates everything onto a 3.5″ × 2.0″ board. The width was constrained\n by the keyboard footprint, which sets the device's overall size, with the remaining\n space alongside the board reserved for the LiPo.\n </p>\n<p>\n The routing was more involved than a typical ESP32 layout because the display libraries\n required specific HSPI and FSPI default pins with no GPIO matrix remapping. Where\n traces would otherwise conflict, they cross layers via vias — technical debt the\n software forced onto the PCB. The ESP32 module hangs slightly off the board edge and\n a copper keep-out preserves the antenna's 2.4GHz performance. All passives are 0603;\n all ICs are SOIC or SOT-23 for hand solderability.\n </p>"
        },
        {
          "h": "What's Next",
          "html": "<p>\n The current PCB design works, but it's a first pass at consolidating the prototype. A few\n things I'd change in the next revision.\n </p>\n01\n<h3>Proper Hinge Connector</h3>\n<p>\n The through-hole headers connecting the displays would go. A proper board-to-board\n connector between the main PCB and a small display adapter board on the hinged upper\n half would be cleaner and more durable than the current ribbon of wires running through\n the hinge, which is acceptable on a prototype but not on something you'd want to carry\n around daily.\n </p>\n02\n<h3>Display Sizing</h3>\n<p>\n The displays themselves don't quite match the keyboard's footprint. The TFT is close,\n but the ePaper is noticeably narrower than the keyboard below it. A future version\n would use displays sized to match. The ePaper in particular has a lot of room to grow\n without changing the physical concept at all.\n </p>\n03\n<h3>Buck Converter for Efficiency</h3>\n<p>\n On the power side, replacing the linear 3.3V regulator with a buck converter would\n help battery life, especially since the ESP32 draws enough current that the LDO\n dissipates a meaningful amount of heat at full load. It wasn't worth the PCB complexity\n for this design pass, but it would be worth it for a polished version.\n </p>\n<h3>Repository</h3>\n<p>\n All firmware, KiCad files, schematics, gerbers, and BOM are on GitHub.\n </p>\n<a href=\"https://github.com/BeckettMazeau/EDES301\">View on GitHub →</a>\n<p>Built at Rice University, Spring 2026. EDES 301.</p>"
        }
